{"type":"user","message":{"role":"user","content":[{"tool_use_id":"toolu_01USRxUFRmPHm4xAdf7Vd1BQ","type":"tool_result","content":"     1â†’# Workflows\n     2â†’\n     3â†’Cloche workflows define a directed graph of steps connected by named results.\n     4â†’\n     5â†’## Workflow Locations\n     6â†’\n     7â†’Cloche distinguishes two workflow locations based on the file they live in:\n     8â†’\n     9â†’**Container workflows** (`.cloche/*.cloche` except `host.cloche`) â€” Run inside a Docker\n    10â†’container via `cloche-agent`. Steps may only be `agent` or `script` type. These are the\n    11â†’standard workflows for coding tasks.\n    12â†’\n    13â†’**Host workflows** (`.cloche/host.cloche`) â€” Run on the host machine as the daemon\n    14â†’process. Steps may be `agent`, `script`, or `workflow` type. The `workflow` step type\n    15â†’dispatches a container workflow run and waits for it to complete. This is the extension\n    16â†’point for custom orchestration strategies.\n    17â†’\n    18â†’A single `host.cloche` file may contain **multiple named workflows**. The daemon\n    19â†’uses up to three workflow phases for orchestration:\n    20â†’\n    21â†’| Phase | Workflow name | Purpose |\n    22â†’|-------|--------------|---------|\n    23â†’| 1 | `list-tasks` | Discover available work. Output is JSONL (one task per line). |\n    24â†’| 2 | `main` | Do the work. Receives a task ID via `CLOCHE_TASK_ID` env var. |\n    25â†’| 3 | `finalize` | Post-main cleanup. Runs on **both** success and failure. |\n    26â†’\n    27â†’Only `main` is required. If `list-tasks` is absent, the daemon uses a legacy\n    28â†’single-function mode. If `finalize` is absent, it is skipped.\n    29â†’\n    30â†’The `list-tasks` workflow's final step output is parsed as JSONL. Each line is a JSON\n    31â†’object with the following fields:\n    32â†’\n    33â†’| Field | Required | Description |\n    34â†’|-------|----------|-------------|\n    35â†’| `id` | yes | Unique task identifier |\n    36â†’| `status` | yes | One of `open`, `closed`, `in-progress` |\n    37â†’| `title` | no | Short summary |\n    38â†’| `description` | no | Full description |\n    39â†’| `metadata` | no | Arbitrary key-value pairs |\n    40â†’\n    41â†’The daemon picks the first task with status `open` (or empty, for backward\n    42â†’compatibility), runs `main` with that task ID, then runs `finalize` with the outcome.\n    43â†’Tasks are deduplicated within a configurable timeout window to prevent rapid\n    44â†’reassignment.\n    45â†’\n    46â†’The convention is enforced at parse time: a `workflow_name` step in a container workflow\n    47â†’file is a parse error.\n    48â†’\n    49â†’## Concepts\n    50â†’\n    51â†’| Concept  | Description                                                        |\n    52â†’|----------|--------------------------------------------------------------------|\n    53â†’| workflow | A named graph of steps connected by result wiring                  |\n    54â†’| step     | A unit of work (inferred: `prompt` = agent, `run` = script)        |\n    55â†’| result   | A named outcome reported by a step (e.g. \"success\", \"fail\")       |\n    56â†’| wiring   | Maps a step's result to the next step, with optional output mappings |\n    57â†’| done     | Built-in terminal step â€” successful completion                     |\n    58â†’| abort    | Built-in terminal step â€” failure with error reporting              |\n    59â†’\n    60â†’## Step Types\n    61â†’\n    62â†’Step type is inferred from the fields present in the step body:\n    63â†’\n    64â†’**agent** (has `prompt`) â€” Invokes a coding agent (Claude Code, or any tool conforming\n    65â†’to the agent adapter interface) with a prompt. The agent works autonomously inside the\n    66â†’container. Available in both host and container workflows.\n    67â†’\n    68â†’**script** (has `run`) â€” Runs a shell command. Used for tests, linters, validators, or\n    69â†’any deterministic check. Available in both host and container workflows.\n    70â†’\n    71â†’**workflow** (has `workflow_name`) â€” Dispatches a named container workflow run and blocks\n    72â†’until it completes. Only available in host workflows (`host.cloche`).\n    73â†’\n    74â†’A step with more than one of `prompt`, `run`, or `workflow_name`, or none of them, is a\n    75â†’parse error.\n    76â†’\n    77â†’## DSL Syntax\n    78â†’\n    79â†’```\n    80â†’workflow \"implement-feature\" {\n    81â†’  step code {\n    82â†’    prompt = file(\".cloche/prompts/implement.md\")\n    83â†’    container {\n    84â†’      image = \"cloche/agent:latest\"\n    85â†’      network_allow = [\"docs.python.org\"]\n    86â†’    }\n    87â†’    results = [success, fail, retry_with_feedback]\n    88â†’  }\n    89â†’\n    90â†’  step check {\n    91â†’    run = \"make test && make lint\"\n    92â†’    results = [pass, fail]\n    93â†’  }\n    94â†’\n    95â†’  step review {\n    96â†’    prompt = file(\".cloche/prompts/review.md\")\n    97â†’    input = step.code.output\n    98â†’    results = [approved, changes_requested]\n    99â†’  }\n   100â†’\n   101â†’  // Wiring: step:result -> next_step [optional output mappings]\n   102â†’  code:success -> check\n   103â†’  code:fail -> abort\n   104â†’  code:retry_with_feedback -> code\n   105â†’\n   106â†’  check:pass -> review\n   107â†’  check:fail -> code:retry_with_feedback\n   108â†’\n   109â†’  review:approved -> done\n   110â†’  review:changes_requested -> code\n   111â†’}\n   112â†’```\n   113â†’\n   114â†’## Key Properties\n   115â†’\n   116â†’**Step type is inferred from content.** A `prompt` field makes it an agent step; a `run`\n   117â†’field makes it a script step.\n   118â†’\n   119â†’**Steps declare their possible results.** A step decides at runtime which result to\n   120â†’report. The graph engine follows the wiring to determine the next step.\n   121â†’\n   122â†’**Wiring is separate from step definitions.** This enables inserting new steps between\n   123â†’existing ones by rewiring â€” without modifying either step. This is the foundation for\n   124â†’Cloche's self-evolution feature.\n   125â†’\n   126â†’**Graphs are validated at parse time.** The parser checks that all declared results are\n   127â†’wired, no steps are orphaned, and an entry point exists.\n   128â†’\n   129â†’## Wire Output Mappings\n   130â†’\n   131â†’Wires can include output mappings that extract values from a step's output and inject\n   132â†’them as environment variables into the target step:\n   133â†’\n   134â†’```\n   135â†’step-a:success -> step-b [ ENV_VAR = output.field, OTHER = output.list[0].name ]\n   136â†’```\n   137â†’\n   138â†’The general form:\n   139â†’\n   140â†’```\n   141â†’FROM:RESULT -> TO [ KEY = EXPR, KEY = EXPR, ... ]\n   142â†’```\n   143â†’\n   144â†’Where `KEY` is the environment variable name and `EXPR` is an output path expression\n   145â†’starting with the contextual keyword `output`:\n   146â†’\n   147â†’| Expression | Meaning |\n   148â†’|---|---|\n   149â†’| `output` | Raw output (full string) |\n   150â†’| `output.key` | JSON object field access |\n   151â†’| `output[N]` | JSON array index (0-based) |\n   152â†’| `output.a.b.c` | Deeply nested field access |\n   153â†’| `output.items[0].name` | Mixed field and index chaining |\n   154â†’\n   155â†’If the source step's output is valid JSON, path expressions navigate the parsed\n   156â†’structure. If the output is plain text, only bare `output` is valid. The resolved\n   157â†’value is converted to a string for env var injection.\n   158â†’\n   159â†’If two wires targeting the same step both map the same env var key, validation\n   160â†’returns an error (the mapping would be ambiguous). The same key may be used on\n   161â†’wires to different steps without conflict.\n   162â†’\n   163â†’## The `host {}` Block\n   164â†’\n   165â†’Host workflows support a `host {}` block at the workflow level to configure agent\n   166â†’defaults for agent steps running on the host machine. Keys are stored with a `host.`\n   167â†’prefix, analogous to the `container {}` block for container workflows.\n   168â†’\n   169â†’```\n   170â†’workflow \"main\" {\n   171â†’  host {\n   172â†’    agent_command = \"claude\"\n   173â†’  }\n   174â†’  ...\n   175â†’}\n   176â†’```\n   177â†’\n   178â†’Supported keys: `agent_command`, `agent_args`. Step-level `agent_command` and\n   179â†’`agent_args` override the workflow-level `host {}` defaults. The agent command\n   180â†’resolution order for host agent steps is the same as for container agent steps:\n   181â†’step-level > workflow-level `host {}` > `CLOCHE_AGENT_COMMAND` env var > default\n   182â†’`claude`.\n   183â†’\n   184â†’## Host Workflow Example\n   185â†’\n   186â†’A three-phase `host.cloche` with separate `list-tasks`, `main`, and `finalize`\n   187â†’workflows:\n   188â†’\n   189â†’```\n   190â†’# .cloche/host.cloche â€” runs on the host machine\n   191â†’\n   192â†’workflow \"list-tasks\" {\n   193â†’  step fetch-tickets {\n   194â†’    run     = \"bash .cloche/scripts/ready-tasks.sh\"\n   195â†’    results = [success, fail]\n   196â†’  }\n   197â†’\n   198â†’  fetch-tickets:success -> done\n   199â†’  fetch-tickets:fail    -> abort\n   200â†’}\n   201â†’\n   202â†’workflow \"main\" {\n   203â†’  host {\n   204â†’    agent_command = \"claude\"\n   205â†’  }\n   206â†’\n   207â†’  step prepare-prompt {\n   208â†’    run     = \"bash .cloche/scripts/prepare-prompt.sh\"\n   209â†’    results = [success, fail]\n   210â†’  }\n   211â†’\n   212â†’  step develop {\n   213â†’    workflow_name = \"develop\"\n   214â†’    results       = [success, fail]\n   215â†’  }\n   216â†’\n   217â†’  prepare-prompt:success -> develop\n   218â†’  prepare-prompt:fail    -> abort\n   219â†’  develop:success        -> done\n   220â†’  develop:fail           -> done\n   221â†’}\n   222â†’\n   223â†’workflow \"finalize\" {\n   224â†’  step push-for-review {\n   225â†’    run     = \"bash .cloche/scripts/push-for-review.sh\"\n   226â†’    results = [success, fail]\n   227â†’  }\n   228â†’\n   229â†’  push-for-review:success -> done\n   230â†’  push-for-review:fail    -> done\n   231â†’}\n   232â†’```\n   233â†’\n   234â†’The daemon runs `list-tasks` to discover work (output is JSONL), picks an open task,\n   235â†’runs `main` with `CLOCHE_TASK_ID` set, then runs `finalize` regardless of outcome.\n   236â†’The `list-tasks` script writes one JSON object per line to `$CLOCHE_STEP_OUTPUT`.\n   237â†’The `main` workflow receives the task ID and is responsible for claiming the ticket.\n   238â†’The `finalize` workflow decides what to do based on the outcome (available via\n   239â†’`CLOCHE_MAIN_OUTCOME` and `CLOCHE_MAIN_RUN_ID` env vars).\n   240â†’\n   241â†’## Execution Model\n   242â†’\n   243â†’**Container workflows** are parsed and executed by `cloche-agent` inside a Docker\n   244â†’container. The agent walks the graph: execute current step, read its result, follow the\n   245â†’wiring to the next step. This continues until a terminal (`done` or `abort`) is reached.\n   246â†’All steps run inside the same container. File state accumulates naturally across steps.\n   247â†’\n   248â†’**Host workflows** are parsed and executed by the daemon on the host machine. A single\n   249â†’`host.cloche` file may contain multiple named workflows; the daemon orchestrates them\n   250â†’in three phases (list-tasks â†’ main â†’ finalize). Script steps run via `sh -c` with the\n   251â†’working directory set to the **main git worktree** (i.e. the main branch checkout), even\n   252â†’if the project directory is a linked worktree on a different branch. This ensures\n   253â†’host-workflow scripts from main are used for all runs. Workflow steps dispatch container\n   254â†’runs via the daemon's standard run pipeline. Environment variables (`CLOCHE_TASK_ID`,\n   255â†’`CLOCHE_PROJECT_DIR`, etc.) are injected into each step; `CLOCHE_PROJECT_DIR` still\n   256â†’points to the actual project directory.\n   257â†’"}]},"parent_tool_use_id":null,"session_id":"9eafd946-92ce-4081-bfc6-e705f31b605b","uuid":"96f38f26-3d66-4be8-ac5a-a731cdd3be16","tool_use_result":{"type":"text","file":{"filePath":"/workspace/docs/workflows.md","content":"# Workflows\n\nCloche workflows define a directed graph of steps connected by named results.\n\n## Workflow Locations\n\nCloche distinguishes two workflow locations based on the file they live in:\n\n**Container workflows** (`.cloche/*.cloche` except `host.cloche`) â€” Run inside a Docker\ncontainer via `cloche-agent`. Steps may only be `agent` or `script` type. These are the\nstandard workflows for coding tasks.\n\n**Host workflows** (`.cloche/host.cloche`) â€” Run on the host machine as the daemon\nprocess. Steps may be `agent`, `script`, or `workflow` type. The `workflow` step type\ndispatches a container workflow run and waits for it to complete. This is the extension\npoint for custom orchestration strategies.\n\nA single `host.cloche` file may contain **multiple named workflows**. The daemon\nuses up to three workflow phases for orchestration:\n\n| Phase | Workflow name | Purpose |\n|-------|--------------|---------|\n| 1 | `list-tasks` | Discover available work. Output is JSONL (one task per line). |\n| 2 | `main` | Do the work. Receives a task ID via `CLOCHE_TASK_ID` env var. |\n| 3 | `finalize` | Post-main cleanup. Runs on **both** success and failure. |\n\nOnly `main` is required. If `list-tasks` is absent, the daemon uses a legacy\nsingle-function mode. If `finalize` is absent, it is skipped.\n\nThe `list-tasks` workflow's final step output is parsed as JSONL. Each line is a JSON\nobject with the following fields:\n\n| Field | Required | Description |\n|-------|----------|-------------|\n| `id` | yes | Unique task identifier |\n| `status` | yes | One of `open`, `closed`, `in-progress` |\n| `title` | no | Short summary |\n| `description` | no | Full description |\n| `metadata` | no | Arbitrary key-value pairs |\n\nThe daemon picks the first task with status `open` (or empty, for backward\ncompatibility), runs `main` with that task ID, then runs `finalize` with the outcome.\nTasks are deduplicated within a configurable timeout window to prevent rapid\nreassignment.\n\nThe convention is enforced at parse time: a `workflow_name` step in a container workflow\nfile is a parse error.\n\n## Concepts\n\n| Concept  | Description                                                        |\n|----------|--------------------------------------------------------------------|\n| workflow | A named graph of steps connected by result wiring                  |\n| step     | A unit of work (inferred: `prompt` = agent, `run` = script)        |\n| result   | A named outcome reported by a step (e.g. \"success\", \"fail\")       |\n| wiring   | Maps a step's result to the next step, with optional output mappings |\n| done     | Built-in terminal step â€” successful completion                     |\n| abort    | Built-in terminal step â€” failure with error reporting              |\n\n## Step Types\n\nStep type is inferred from the fields present in the step body:\n\n**agent** (has `prompt`) â€” Invokes a coding agent (Claude Code, or any tool conforming\nto the agent adapter interface) with a prompt. The agent works autonomously inside the\ncontainer. Available in both host and container workflows.\n\n**script** (has `run`) â€” Runs a shell command. Used for tests, linters, validators, or\nany deterministic check. Available in both host and container workflows.\n\n**workflow** (has `workflow_name`) â€” Dispatches a named container workflow run and blocks\nuntil it completes. Only available in host workflows (`host.cloche`).\n\nA step with more than one of `prompt`, `run`, or `workflow_name`, or none of them, is a\nparse error.\n\n## DSL Syntax\n\n```\nworkflow \"implement-feature\" {\n  step code {\n    prompt = file(\".cloche/prompts/implement.md\")\n    container {\n      image = \"cloche/agent:latest\"\n      network_allow = [\"docs.python.org\"]\n    }\n    results = [success, fail, retry_with_feedback]\n  }\n\n  step check {\n    run = \"make test && make lint\"\n    results = [pass, fail]\n  }\n\n  step review {\n    prompt = file(\".cloche/prompts/review.md\")\n    input = step.code.output\n    results = [approved, changes_requested]\n  }\n\n  // Wiring: step:result -> next_step [optional output mappings]\n  code:success -> check\n  code:fail -> abort\n  code:retry_with_feedback -> code\n\n  check:pass -> review\n  check:fail -> code:retry_with_feedback\n\n  review:approved -> done\n  review:changes_requested -> code\n}\n```\n\n## Key Properties\n\n**Step type is inferred from content.** A `prompt` field makes it an agent step; a `run`\nfield makes it a script step.\n\n**Steps declare their possible results.** A step decides at runtime which result to\nreport. The graph engine follows the wiring to determine the next step.\n\n**Wiring is separate from step definitions.** This enables inserting new steps between\nexisting ones by rewiring â€” without modifying either step. This is the foundation for\nCloche's self-evolution feature.\n\n**Graphs are validated at parse time.** The parser checks that all declared results are\nwired, no steps are orphaned, and an entry point exists.\n\n## Wire Output Mappings\n\nWires can include output mappings that extract values from a step's output and inject\nthem as environment variables into the target step:\n\n```\nstep-a:success -> step-b [ ENV_VAR = output.field, OTHER = output.list[0].name ]\n```\n\nThe general form:\n\n```\nFROM:RESULT -> TO [ KEY = EXPR, KEY = EXPR, ... ]\n```\n\nWhere `KEY` is the environment variable name and `EXPR` is an output path expression\nstarting with the contextual keyword `output`:\n\n| Expression | Meaning |\n|---|---|\n| `output` | Raw output (full string) |\n| `output.key` | JSON object field access |\n| `output[N]` | JSON array index (0-based) |\n| `output.a.b.c` | Deeply nested field access |\n| `output.items[0].name` | Mixed field and index chaining |\n\nIf the source step's output is valid JSON, path expressions navigate the parsed\nstructure. If the output is plain text, only bare `output` is valid. The resolved\nvalue is converted to a string for env var injection.\n\nIf two wires targeting the same step both map the same env var key, validation\nreturns an error (the mapping would be ambiguous). The same key may be used on\nwires to different steps without conflict.\n\n## The `host {}` Block\n\nHost workflows support a `host {}` block at the workflow level to configure agent\ndefaults for agent steps running on the host machine. Keys are stored with a `host.`\nprefix, analogous to the `container {}` block for container workflows.\n\n```\nworkflow \"main\" {\n  host {\n    agent_command = \"claude\"\n  }\n  ...\n}\n```\n\nSupported keys: `agent_command`, `agent_args`. Step-level `agent_command` and\n`agent_args` override the workflow-level `host {}` defaults. The agent command\nresolution order for host agent steps is the same as for container agent steps:\nstep-level > workflow-level `host {}` > `CLOCHE_AGENT_COMMAND` env var > default\n`claude`.\n\n## Host Workflow Example\n\nA three-phase `host.cloche` with separate `list-tasks`, `main`, and `finalize`\nworkflows:\n\n```\n# .cloche/host.cloche â€” runs on the host machine\n\nworkflow \"list-tasks\" {\n  step fetch-tickets {\n    run     = \"bash .cloche/scripts/ready-tasks.sh\"\n    results = [success, fail]\n  }\n\n  fetch-tickets:success -> done\n  fetch-tickets:fail    -> abort\n}\n\nworkflow \"main\" {\n  host {\n    agent_command = \"claude\"\n  }\n\n  step prepare-prompt {\n    run     = \"bash .cloche/scripts/prepare-prompt.sh\"\n    results = [success, fail]\n  }\n\n  step develop {\n    workflow_name = \"develop\"\n    results       = [success, fail]\n  }\n\n  prepare-prompt:success -> develop\n  prepare-prompt:fail    -> abort\n  develop:success        -> done\n  develop:fail           -> done\n}\n\nworkflow \"finalize\" {\n  step push-for-review {\n    run     = \"bash .cloche/scripts/push-for-review.sh\"\n    results = [success, fail]\n  }\n\n  push-for-review:success -> done\n  push-for-review:fail    -> done\n}\n```\n\nThe daemon runs `list-tasks` to discover work (output is JSONL), picks an open task,\nruns `main` with `CLOCHE_TASK_ID` set, then runs `finalize` regardless of outcome.\nThe `list-tasks` script writes one JSON object per line to `$CLOCHE_STEP_OUTPUT`.\nThe `main` workflow receives the task ID and is responsible for claiming the ticket.\nThe `finalize` workflow decides what to do based on the outcome (available via\n`CLOCHE_MAIN_OUTCOME` and `CLOCHE_MAIN_RUN_ID` env vars).\n\n## Execution Model\n\n**Container workflows** are parsed and executed by `cloche-agent` inside a Docker\ncontainer. The agent walks the graph: execute current step, read its result, follow the\nwiring to the next step. This continues until a terminal (`done` or `abort`) is reached.\nAll steps run inside the same container. File state accumulates naturally across steps.\n\n**Host workflows** are parsed and executed by the daemon on the host machine. A single\n`host.cloche` file may contain multiple named workflows; the daemon orchestrates them\nin three phases (list-tasks â†’ main â†’ finalize). Script steps run via `sh -c` with the\nworking directory set to the **main git worktree** (i.e. the main branch checkout), even\nif the project directory is a linked worktree on a different branch. This ensures\nhost-workflow scripts from main are used for all runs. Workflow steps dispatch container\nruns via the daemon's standard run pipeline. Environment variables (`CLOCHE_TASK_ID`,\n`CLOCHE_PROJECT_DIR`, etc.) are injected into each step; `CLOCHE_PROJECT_DIR` still\npoints to the actual project directory.\n","numLines":257,"startLine":1,"totalLines":257}}}
{"type":"assistant","message":{"model":"claude-opus-4-6","id":"msg_01BWeVE8n7x91nXo2d4RpqRi","type":"message","role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"thinking","thinking":"Now let me analyze the changes and compare against docs:\n\n1. **New `cloche tasks` CLI command** - Not documented in USAGE.md CLI Reference. Needs to be added.\n2. **New web API endpoint `GET /api/projects/{name}/tasks`** - This is an internal API, docs don't typically document web API endpoints individually.\n3. **Run ID format changed** from `<workflow>-<adj>-<noun>` to `<workflow>-<adj>-<noun>-<hex>` - Let me check if the old format is mentioned in docs.\n4. **`TaskProvider` interface, `TaskEntry` type** - internal, not documented.\n\n\n5. **`GetTaskSnapshot()` method on Loop** - also internal. Now I'm checking whether the run ID format change is documented anywhere in the existing docs.","signature":""}],"stop_reason":null,"stop_sequence":null,"usage":{"input_tokens":1,"cache_creation_input_tokens":11282,"cache_read_input_tokens":24480,"cache_creation":{"ephemeral_5m_input_tokens":0,"ephemeral_1h_input_tokens":11282},"output_tokens":8,"service_tier":"standard","inference_geo":"not_available"},"context_management":null},"parent_tool_use_id":null,"session_id":"9eafd946-92ce-4081-bfc6-e705f31b605b","uuid":"063e4982-85f0-4dbe-9e02-befb136d5330"}
